        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Polit.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " i. 10. 5): it was also shared largely in the early Christian Church. Many good Christians, however, now put out their money on interest: what, then, is the cause of the change of feeling? The cause is to be found in the different purpose for which money is now lent. In modern times money is commonly lent for ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "commercial",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " purposes, to enable the borrower to increase his capital and develope his business: and it is as natural and proper that a reasonable payment should be made for the accommodation, as that it should be made for this loan (i.e. the hire) of a house, or any other commodity. But this use of loans is a modern development: in ancient times money was commonly lent for the relief of poverty brought about by misfortune or debt; it partook thus of the nature of a ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "charity",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; and to take interest on money thus lent was felt to be making gain out of a neighbour’s need. The interest which ancient feeling condemned was thus not the interest taken on a ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "commercial",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " loan such as is taken habitually in the modern world, but the interest taken on a ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "charitable",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " loan, which only increases the borrower’s distress. Be the feeling with which the ancients regarded ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "all",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " interest is of course still rightly maintained against ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "usurious",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " interest, such as ‘money-lenders’ often exact from those whom need drives into their hands. Cf. the remarks of Grote, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Hist. of Greece",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", Part II., ch. xi., in connexion with the measures adopted by Solon at Athens for the relief of those who had borrowed money on the security of their own persons (cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 4:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ").",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
