  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verses 25-27.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "The law of lending money and borrowing",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". It is peculiar to the Jewish law to forbid the lending of money at interest by citizen to citizen. In the present passage, and in some others (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 25:35",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 15:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), it might seem that interest was only forbidden in the case of a loan to one who was poor; but the general execration of usury (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Job 24:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Proverbs 28:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezekiel 18:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezekiel 22:12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and the description of the righteous man as \"he that hath not given his money upon usury\" (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 15:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezekiel 18:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), seem rather to imply that the practice, so far as Israelites were concerned, was forbidden altogether. On the other hand, it was distinctly declared (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 23:20",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") that interest might be taken from strangers. There does not seem to have been any rate of interest which was regarded as excessive, and \"usurious,\" in the modern sense. In Scripture usury means simply interest. Exodus 22:25",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "If a man should lend to one of the poor of his own people, he was not to oppress him by demanding interest; and if he gave his upper garment as a pledge, he was to give it him back towards sunset, because it was his only covering; as the poorer classes in the East use the upper garment, consisting of a large square piece of cloth, to sleep in. \"It is his clothing for his skin:\" i.e., it serves for a covering to his body. \"Wherein shall he lie?\" i.e., in what shall be wrap himself to sleep? (cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 24:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 24:10-13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). - With ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 22:28",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". God directs Himself at once to the hearts of the Israelites, and attacks the sins of selfishness and covetousness, against which the precepts in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 22:21-27",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " were directed in their deepest root, for the purpose of opposing all inward resistance to the promotion of His commands. ",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
